  "opinion": "As a 40-year-old plumber living in Naples, I see fake content on social media like a leaky pipe—it’s a nuisance that can cause real damage if ignored. I spend about an hour daily on platforms, mostly to unwind after work or connect with friends, so I’ve learned to spot misinformation quickly. My vocational diploma taught me hands-on problem-solving, and that applies here: you don’t need a fancy degree to be skeptical. For instance, when I see a viral post about a plumbing hack that seems too good to be true, I check reliable sources or ask colleagues before sharing. My parents, with their advanced education, always stressed critical thinking, which helps me question sensational headlines. As an immigrant, I’ve faced stereotypes online, so I’m cautious about content that spreads hate or falsehoods about communities. My creative side enjoys board games and travel, and I apply that curiosity to dig deeper—like verifying travel deals or event details before acting. With high conscientiousness, I take responsibility for what I post, ensuring it’s accurate to avoid misleading others. My low agreeableness means I’m not afraid to call out fake news in discussions, even if it ruffles feathers. In Islam, truthfulness is valued, so I align my online behavior with that principle. To manage fake content, I recommend a practical approach: verify with trusted sources, limit sharing until confirmed, and use platform tools to report misinformation. It’s about being proactive, like fixing a small drip before it floods the house.",
